	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Thirteen Ways Of Claiming A Literary Prize</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/erin-van-rheenen">Erin Van Rheenen</a></li><li><a href="/issues/335">November 2003</a></li></ul>

			</div>

																			

				<figure class="block-content-photo block-content-photo-large photo photo-outset-center-large">
					
					<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 2360 1606'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1180x1734r/photos/1524772047_335-12-townsend.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/2360x3468r/photos/1524772047_335-12-townsend.jpg
	 alt="335 - Townsend - Rheenen"
	 class="lazy">

										<figcaption>

						
																				<div class="photo-credit">
								&copy;&nbsp;<a href="/contributors/mark-townsend">Mark Townsend</a>
							</div>
																		</figcaption>
									</figure>

					</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<h5>1.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>&ldquo;There he is,&rdquo;</strong></span> someone whispered.</p>

<p>At the other end of the bar stood a stocky man with thinning hair and black-rimmed glasses. His skin gave off an unhealthy sheen; his eyes swam, magnified and vague, behind thick lenses. So this was the Pulitzer Prize&ndash;winning author (let&rsquo;s call him Moe) who&rsquo;d chosen my unpublished book as best new novel.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;d gotten the call almost a year earlier. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t believe it&rdquo; was my response. I was serious. I&rsquo;d forgotten I&rsquo;d even entered the contest, and I suspected that Joe DeSalvo, cofounder of the Faulkner Society and bearer of these good tidings, was an especially wily telemarketer. Next he&rsquo;d offer me his editing services at a very reasonable fee.</p>

<p>Instead I got a check, which helped me stay happily under-employed for another six months, and a free trip to New Orleans to claim my Faulkner-headed gold medal. The society bestowing the prize was less than ten years old; the prize was not well-known but had the advantage of being easily confused with the prestigious PEN/Faulkner award, which was conferred upon a published book rather than a promising manuscript.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;d arrived in New Orleans to claim my prize, but the threat of Hurricane Georges had sent everyone running; the society had graciously invited all of the winners back this year. Now my husband Osvaldo and I were shivering in the air-conditioned ballroom of the Fairmont Hotel. (We&rsquo;d dressed for the New Orleans heat.)</p>

<p>Besides the check, what had thrilled me most was the prospect of meeting Moe and getting his response to my novel. In the year since I&rsquo;d won, I had written him a few times but had received no reply. Surely a face-to-face meeting would bear fruit. Toiling alone, as all writers do, I&rsquo;d completely rewritten my book; no editor had yet laid eyes on the rewrite. Would Moe agree to be its first reader?</p>

<p>Swallowing the last of a screwdriver and grabbing Osvaldo by the hand, I made my way over to Moe and his pretty blond wife.</p>

<p>As I approached, vague ideas of master-apprentice relationships floated through my head. I&rsquo;d never had a mentor. When older people had offered advice or help, I&rsquo;d reacted with suspicion, wondering what they wanted in return. Now I knew I needed help, and probably always would need it, but I had reached the age at which I should have been a mentor myself. Just as I was ready to be taken under someone&rsquo;s wing, I was too big to fit.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Are you Mr. Moe?&rdquo; I asked.</p>

<p>He nodded.</p>

<p>I introduced myself. I didn&rsquo;t mention the letters he had never answered.</p>

<p>There was a long silence.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Do you live here in New Orleans?&rdquo; his wife finally said, trying to place me.</p>

<p>&ldquo;We live in San Francisco,&rdquo; I said, putting my hand on Osvaldo&rsquo;s arm.</p>

<p>Another silence.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I wrote <em>Written on Water</em>,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;Now it&rsquo;s <em>The Gospel of Gone</em>. It won the novel prize.&rdquo; I tried to pin down his eyes with my own, but they were as blurred as a bad snapshot. &ldquo;Last year.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, yes, yes,&rdquo; he said hurriedly, looking over my head, across the room, down at the floor. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t remember. Were we in contact?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I wrote you,&rdquo; I said. <em>And didn&rsquo;t hear back</em>, I didn&rsquo;t say. Not hearing back is nothing remarkable for most writers. We knock on closed doors until our knuckles bleed. But the celebrated author who chooses your book from among hundreds &mdash; he had to open the door, if only just a crack, to say, <em>Well done!</em> Or, <em>Keep at it!</em> Which would suffice, although it was much less than what we all want to hear: <em>You, my friend, are a genius!</em></p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Now I remember. I&rsquo;ve been so busy. I just came back from Australia.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I heard silverware clang, laughter erupt and die out. <em>Do you think the book&rsquo;s ending works?</em> I wanted to ask, but I couldn&rsquo;t find a way to shoehorn it into the nonconversation.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s too bad you and your wife have to leave so soon,&rdquo; I finally managed to say. They were flying out early the next morning, which meant Moe wouldn&rsquo;t be able to give me my medal at the awards ceremony.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; he agreed, turning away. I echoed his pivot, just a second or two behind, a student mimicking the master.</p>

<p>I couldn&rsquo;t eat my dinner but managed to suck down three more screwdrivers and two helpings of bread pudding with rum sauce. Between gulps I looked around. There was Robert Olen Butler at the buffet table, poking at a platter of meat. This year&rsquo;s novel judge (let&rsquo;s call her LuAnn) sat demurely a few tables away, her bright blue eyes and lacquered fingernails visible even from this distance. Her nails were a silky, dangerous black.</p>

<p>A few tables away from LuAnn sat the woman who&rsquo;d been runner-up in three contest categories. She kept telling the winners, with a tremor in her voice, how very, very happy she was for them.</p>

<p>On the plane ride there I&rsquo;d devised a trick for keeping my bearings in this august atmosphere: I would repeat to myself, as often as necessary, <em>It&rsquo;s a big world, and you&rsquo;re a big girl</em>. Winning this prize was great, but it didn&rsquo;t necessarily mean I was on my way to fame and fortune, or even publication. I still had my talented, mostly obscure artist friends who struggled to write, paint, craft jewelry, or make films, and I had the solitary pleasure of sitting down to whatever story I happened to be working on that week, or month, or year.</p>

<p>And the world was bigger than fiction; like the convention of osteopaths meeting in a nearby hotel, fiction writers were just another microculture. Flexibility was the key to a writing career; I could always teach, or edit, or write website copy. And whatever happened, I was a big girl; I could take it.</p>

<p>But big girls do cry, and that night in our hotel room Osvaldo had his hands full trying to console me. &ldquo;I should have punched the pig,&rdquo; he said in the early hours of the morning, which made me feel only a little better.</p>

<p>It wasn&rsquo;t the first time my naivet&eacute; had done me in. At a conference billed as a &ldquo;community of writers&rdquo; I had incurred the organizers&rsquo; scorn for believing it to be just that. The brochure had promised that each participant would meet with one of the moderately successful writers teaching at the event. When I checked the schedule and saw that I&rsquo;d been paired with an agent, I went to see if I could get a writer instead. (I already had an agent, who told me that I&rsquo;d soon be able to live off my writing, but never returned my calls.)</p>

<p>&ldquo;Did you hear the one about the Polish starlet?&rdquo; sneered the scheduler, whose novel was soon to be a major motion picture. &ldquo;She slept with a writer.&rdquo;</p>

<h5>2.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>The day after</strong></span> I met Moe, I was in a conference room at the Monte Leon Hotel, shivering in the air conditioning and wondering what &ldquo;Tango with the Spirits: Sex, Angels, and Avatars&rdquo; would bring. Panels had been meeting at a rate of six or seven a day since the conference had opened. They had titles like &ldquo;The Landscapes of Literature: Paranoia, Politicians, and Prostitutes&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Big Gap: Have We Created an Elite Meritocracy with No Audience?&rdquo; Rosemary James, cofounder of the Faulkner Society, had dreamed up the panel titles and then assigned writers to panels, often not telling them which one they were on until the day before.</p>

<p>I was trying to get ideas for my own panel, the prosaically titled &ldquo;You and Your Editor.&rdquo; I was supposed to contribute the writer&rsquo;s point of view, but since I had no editor, I wasn&rsquo;t sure what to say.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Tango&rdquo; got off to a slow start, with most of the participants admitting that they didn&rsquo;t know what <em>avatar</em> meant. Then panel leader Andrei Codrescu took the floor.</p>

<p>Leaning close to the mike to amplify his familiar Romanian rasp, Codrescu gave a complete and up-to-the-minute definition of <em>avatar</em>, including the Internet definition of a persona you adopt to play games or post messages anonymously. He looked at his copanelists with disapproval, as if to chastise them for trying to pass off ignorance as a lack of pretension.</p>

<p>Then things got really nasty. One panelist said that not only did she not believe in angels or &ldquo;avatars,&rdquo; whatever they were, but that angels in literature irritated her to no end. Isn&rsquo;t real life, she asked, mysterious enough?</p>

<p>A split developed between the New Englanders and the New Orleaners. Codrescu was in the latter camp, growling the virtues of &ldquo;the city like a flower that never closes,&rdquo; land of ghosts, vampires, and women who spill out of their dresses.</p>

<p>Maybe he had something there. New Orleans&rsquo; wet heat definitely acts as a sort of meteorological <span class="smallcaps">PMS</span>, swelling the flesh and giving the city a hysterical edge. All my emotions were right on the surface, and the clothes I&rsquo;d brought from San Francisco felt too tight.</p>

<p>A Northern panelist sang the praises of snow, straight lines, and Scotch on the rocks. Codrescu came back with a remark about Puritanism. This wasn&rsquo;t the first time the War between the States had been revived during the conference. It was almost obligatory for the Southern panelists to testify to the greatness of their region, while the North was evoked as a sort of anti-South, a pale, cold shadow compared to the South&rsquo;s steamy singularity. The West was mentioned only twice that I heard: Montana was &ldquo;where the men dress like men, and so do the women,&rdquo; and San Diego was &ldquo;the bland leading the bland.&rdquo;</p>

<h5>3.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>&ldquo;T.S. Eliot said</strong></span> that most editors are frustrated writers, but most writers are, too.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Was that my voice coming out of the speakers at the back of the room? People in the audience were laughing; was the laughter connected to what I&rsquo;d just said?</p>

<p>Earlier, an author had confessed that what she hated most about speaking in public was that her hands seemed to separate from her body. Now I knew what she meant. My voice was out there on its own, cut off from its creator like a newly published story.</p>

<p>Disassociation aside, it wasn&rsquo;t so bad being in front of an audience, especially when there were only seven or eight people there, half of whom I knew.</p>

<p>I related the story about the editor who&rsquo;d told Nabokov that he&rsquo;d publish <em>Lolita</em> if Nabokov made Lolita a boy and Humbert Humbert a farmer and set the first seduction in a barn. The other panelists, all professional editors, talked about the great collaborative relationship between writer and editor. Maybe, I said, the writer has to fight the editor a little to maintain his or her vision of the book. Maybe there <em>should</em> be a little bit of antagonism between author and editor, just to keep them both honest.</p>

<p>Proud that I&rsquo;d made it through my opening remarks without betraying my terror, I sat back in my chair and looked at my copanelists. What I saw in their eyes was not <em>Welcome to the club</em>. What I saw in their eyes was <em>Now, there&rsquo;s a writer I&rsquo;d never want to work with.</em></p>

<h5>4.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>Later that day,</strong></span> four wildly different writers discussed &ldquo;Fabulous Fables&rdquo;: a medieval scholar spoke of Chaucer; Dalt Wonk read a modern fable of his own; a woman with the face and stillness of a toad offered up a few words on short stories; and A.J. Verdelle, author of <em>The Good Negress</em> and one of the few nonwhite conference participants, spoke of a fable she&rsquo;d written years ago. Osvaldo and I had met Verdelle the previous year, just as everyone was leaving town to escape the hurricane. I&rsquo;d been impressed by her strength, her style, and her dreadlocks, which had lifted in the gathering wind. Later I would read her novel and be even more impressed. A tale of a black girl shunted between her grandmother&rsquo;s home in rural Virginia and her mother&rsquo;s Chicago apartment, the story had that understated pain and big heart that gets me every time.</p>

<p>The fable she&rsquo;d written, Verdelle told the audience, concerned a young girl who saw her mother as a bear. And since the story was from the girl&rsquo;s point of view, the readers also saw the mother as a bear.</p>

<p>&ldquo;People loved that story,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;And I .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo; She grinned. &ldquo;I hated it.&rdquo; She hated it, she said, because it was too predictable, too easy. &ldquo;You win when you take an old story and put just a little newness in it. And they love it when you stick animals in there, when you give them a bear. And if you make the bear talk,&rdquo; she concluded, &ldquo;you win.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Her copanelists nodded, either in agreement or confusion, and the audience was silent, giving her final line the space it deserved.</p>

<p>Although Verdelle spoke with derision of making the bear talk, as if any hack could do it, the idea intrigued me. <em>Just how</em>, I wondered, <em>do you make the bear talk? And what does she say?</em></p>

<h5>5.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>The French Quarter</strong></span> was still very much alive at one o&rsquo;clock on Saturday morning. Jackson Square bristled with fortunetellers, drunks, and vampires &mdash; to be specific, two full-fledged vampires and one wide-eyed female apprentice who passed out glossy leaflets advertising vampire-led cemetery tours while the head vampire staked out a spot on the steps of Saint Louis Cathedral. We were about to see just how far they would go to promote their product.</p>

<p>Flipping his long blond hair over his shoulders, the head vampire raised an arm above his head and sliced into his wrist with a scalpel. Immediately blood ran down his sleeve.</p>

<p>A noose of spectators tightened around him. We moved closer as he wrapped his wrist tightly in gauze. In a showman&rsquo;s baritone he expounded on the forces of evil. Red seeped through the white gauze. We watched silently, almost hungrily, as the force of his heart pumped his private blood out into public.</p>

<p>&ldquo;For the eyeing of my scars,&rdquo; wrote Sylvia Plath in &ldquo;Lady Lazarus,&rdquo; &ldquo;there is a charge.&rdquo; Times have changed. Scars are no longer enough. To get anyone&rsquo;s attention these days, you have to open fresh wounds.</p>

<p>Another circle was forming to our left, in front of the old military garrison. About ten individuals, black and white, mostly in their twenties, joined hands and started chanting. The chant increased in volume from a low murmur to one shouted word: <em>JESUS!</em> The circle swayed, and a call and response started up.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Who is my savior?&rdquo;</p>

<p><em>JESUS!</em></p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, come on,&rdquo; said a man in the vampire&rsquo;s audience.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Who protects me against evil?&rdquo;</p>

<p><em>JESUS!</em></p>

<p>&ldquo;There is a world beneath this one,&rdquo; intoned the bleeding vampire from the cathedral steps. &ldquo;The world of the UNDEAD!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Who lies in wait for the devil?&rdquo; answered the Christians.</p>

<p><em>JESUS!</em></p>

<p>&ldquo;Who&rsquo;s the cat that won&rsquo;t cop out, when there&rsquo;s danger all about? .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. SHAFT!&rdquo; The answer, like the question, came from a solitary voice across the square.</p>

<p>The Jesus folk upped the volume, drowning out the Shaft fan and the vampire on the cathedral steps. &ldquo;Who fears no evil?&rdquo;</p>

<p>A final, deafening <em>JESUS!</em> hung in the warm air a moment before an answering <em>ALLAH!</em> came from the Shaft fan&rsquo;s buddy.</p>

<p>The chants and shouts lingered. Something traveled on the sounds and, still needing to travel, wouldn&rsquo;t let them die down too fast. But finally they wound fully and truly down, and everyone silently agreed that the moment had passed.</p>

<h5>6.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>Osvaldo and I</strong></span> had heard many people sing the praises of New Orleans, but we&rsquo;d heard no song of Canal Street on a Saturday night. It seemed a glaring omission, even though the street, which borders the French Quarter, has about as much old-world charm as a bus terminal. A mix of Marriotts and McDonald&rsquo;s, souvenir shops and high-end department stores, Canal has no wrought-iron balconies to dress up its wide swath of neon and cement. The real show is the people: hordes of humanity, mostly teenagers, all strutting their stuff with such energy and abandon that it was a little, well, scary &mdash; at least it was for someone who&rsquo;s a couple of decades away from that impulse. If they hadn&rsquo;t been so absorbed in showcasing their cars, music, clothes, and bodies, they would have been a force to be reckoned with. (You could say the same about the entire country.)</p>

<p>As it was, you were best advised to stay out of their way: Girls in micro miniskirts dancing on traffic dividers, arms and hips circling like giant chain saws. Shouted conversations across the wide, pitted street. Heavy-duty cruising and preening. Hormones and pheromones making the air a slippery stew.</p>

<p>A beautiful shirtless boy jumped out of a stopped Range Rover and threw himself into an acrobatic dance in the space between lanes. When the light changed, he jumped back in, but the line of cars moved only a few inches before the light turned red again. Once more the boy jumped out, stomped to a spot in front of a group of girls, and went at it, his almost-falling-off pants not slowing him down a bit. The girls incited him further with a lethal blend of admiration and disdain. &ldquo;That all you can do?&rdquo; cajoled one beauty, raking his torso with her eyes.</p>

