</p>

<h5>7.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>I would be</strong></span> the first to receive my medal. LuAnn standing in for the absent Moe, would sling it around my neck, then do the same for this year&rsquo;s winner, Diane Freund. The three of us were sitting backstage at Le Petit Theater with half an hour to kill before the awards ceremony. The bald, smiling theater manager kept telling us we&rsquo;d be more comfortable in the green room.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s much cooler up there,&rdquo; the manager said.</p>

<p>But I, for one, wasn&rsquo;t going to miss my opportunity to be within spitting distance of an author I admired, whose books have that rare quality of something older and stronger than words rising up off the printed page. If LuAnn wanted to go up to the green room, then I&rsquo;d follow.</p>

<p>Up close, she looked older than I&rsquo;d expected, but still gorgeous in a sleeveless velvet tunic, with her blue, blue eyes. She asked me how to pronounce my name &mdash; she&rsquo;d have to say it when she gave me my award. I told her how much her first book had meant to me. &ldquo;I was living in Ecuador when it came out,&rdquo; I told her. &ldquo;Three different people mailed me the book, thinking I&rsquo;d love it. I did. I loved it. It was a voice from a world I&rsquo;d lived in but had never seen on the page &mdash;&rdquo; I stopped. Unlike Moe, LuAnn was looking me in the eye, and there was something in her expression that said, <em>Enough already</em>. &ldquo;It was great,&rdquo; I concluded hurriedly. Oh, to have the luxury of being bored while someone raves about your book.</p>

<p>I let her go, then peered out of the closed curtains to see how the theater looked. Dark, impressive, cold.</p>

<p>A few minutes later I saw LuAnn seated beside Diane, whose novel she had chosen as this year&rsquo;s winner. Diane&rsquo;s manuscript was spread out on their laps, and their heads almost touched as LuAnn pointed out certain lines and passages that she liked, that moved her, or that maybe needed a little more work.</p>

<p>There was a peculiar hollow feeling in the pit of my stomach. I recognized it quickly. It was judge envy.</p>

<h5>8.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>The bald man</strong></span> finally got us to climb the stairs to the chilly green room, which was strewn with tropical-colored overstuffed armchairs. Someone was handing out champagne in plastic cups. LuAnn sat in one corner, still paging through Diane&rsquo;s manuscript. (I would later learn that she&rsquo;d made many detailed suggestions on how to revise it &mdash; saying that the narrator should be eleven instead of seven, for instance, and offering a new title.)</p>

<p>In another corner sat A.J. Verdelle. &ldquo;How are you two?&rdquo; she asked Osvaldo and me.</p>

<p>We told her we were fine. &ldquo;I liked what you said on the fables panel,&rdquo; I said.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I was wondering if I made any sense.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, you did,&rdquo; I assured her. &ldquo;The thing about making the bear talk &mdash; that was a great way to end. I&rsquo;m not sure you meant it this way, but to me it was almost like a riddle, a challenge: how <em>do</em> you make the bear talk?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It kind of felt like I was babbling.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Not at all.&rdquo; In the pause that followed I looked over at LuAnn. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s exciting,&rdquo; I said softly, &ldquo;to get to meet LuAnn. I love her stuff.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;We&rsquo;re buddies,&rdquo; said Verdelle.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Really?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;we&rsquo;re sort of buddies. It&rsquo;s not like we talk about writing or anything.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The theater manager appeared at the door, asking that the first round of award recipients come and wait backstage. He also cautioned us to keep our acceptance speeches as short as possible. &ldquo;So we can all get to the party sooner,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Which is where we all want to be, right?&rdquo;</p>

<p>But where I wanted to be was onstage, getting my medal. I hadn&rsquo;t gone to my high-school, college, or graduate-school graduations. Ceremonies had always seemed extraneous to me. Something had come to an end; why draw it out? But just as I&rsquo;d recently come to realize that I might be open to receiving help, I&rsquo;d begun to think I&rsquo;d missed a lot by refusing to participate in those rituals. If you don&rsquo;t celebrate your achievements, who will?</p>

<p>I was so nervous when I went out to receive my medal that I hardly saw the audience. My acceptance speech was brief. The few photos Osvaldo snapped of me in my moment of triumph are all blurred, because I was in motion.</p>

<p>I slipped backstage, then out into the audience. I watched the winner of last year&rsquo;s story award get his medal and then stand his ground, making the most of the moment. I listened to another author, whose story would soon be coming out as a novel, almost break down as she told the audience how the award had come just as she was about to quit writing.</p>

<p>Everyone took their time; all of the speeches were at least three times as long as mine. Once again, I&rsquo;d worked hard to get someplace, and as soon as I&rsquo;d gotten there, I couldn&rsquo;t wait to leave. I&rsquo;d catapulted myself toward, and then right past, the moment.</p>

<p>Fingering the raised Faulkner head on my medal, I turned it over and read my own name. It was misspelled. <em>Fuck a duck</em>, I thought. <em>Fuck a large, quacking duck.</em></p>

<h5>9.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>After all the awards</strong></span> had been handed out, there were a few speeches by writers who&rsquo;d climbed at least halfway up the slippery rope of fame. One spoke of having found his book up for auction on eBay. The bid started at a lowly two dollars and stayed there for days. Finally the author decided to start a bidding war. He offered $2.50, which turned out to be the winning bid. Later, when he got his own book in the mail, he saw it was a copy he&rsquo;d inscribed to a dear friend.</p>

<p>As I left the theater, a contest judge stopped me to tell me that the screener who&rsquo;d passed my book on to the Faulkner Society committee had absolutely adored the novel. &ldquo;She works for me,&rdquo; he said of the screener. &ldquo;Every day she&rsquo;d come in with a new romance novel. So I thought, <em>If she reads so much, why not put her to work?</em>&rdquo; He smiled at me. &ldquo;She loved your book,&rdquo; he repeated. &ldquo;She just loved it.&rdquo;</p>

<h5>10.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>The postceremony party</strong></span> was held in the garden behind Saint Louis Cathedral. Presiding over the well-dressed crowd was a marble Jesus with his arms opened wide, welcoming the successful, the scrambling, and the rich people who fund such galas. I wandered around under moss-hung trees, watched a white cat slide under a hedge, and looked for the bar.</p>

<p>When I brought two glasses of wine back to the table Osvaldo had staked out, I found LuAnn seated next to us. <em>It&rsquo;s a sign</em>, I thought. (In real life I don&rsquo;t believe in signs, but this wasn&rsquo;t real life, was it?)</p>

<p>After I&rsquo;d sipped most of my wine and talked with everyone else at the table, I turned to LuAnn, who had just finished talking up Diane Freund&rsquo;s book to the agent sitting to her right.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s great that you&rsquo;re so involved with the author whose book you chose,&rdquo; I began, and I proceeded to tell her, in fifty words or less, about my experience with Moe. Even as I spoke I felt silly; what did I expect LuAnn to do? But I was leaving the next morning, and I wanted someone to know about my disappointment. &ldquo;It was almost,&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;as if he didn&rsquo;t read it.&rdquo; It was the first time I&rsquo;d thought seriously of that possibility.</p>

<p>She nodded, her expression placid. &ldquo;He&rsquo;s pulled in all different directions,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;He&rsquo;s very busy. Maybe he had someone else read it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I let this sink in, but not too far. I needed to be alone to bear the full weight of the idea. &ldquo;Or maybe he just read the first few pages,&rdquo; I joked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s something,&rdquo; she said, in a neutral tone that neither condemned nor condoned such a possibility. And then, as if sensing what I was going to do even before the idea had crossed my mind &mdash; to ask if she, this year&rsquo;s judge, would be willing to read the revised manuscript of last year&rsquo;s winner &mdash; she erected an invisible barrier between us that only a die-hard self-promoter would have attempted to scale. I picked up my glass and downed the last of my wine.</p>

<h5>11.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>A blond woman</strong></span> in a low-cut dress sat on a grave. A palm reader, she had offered to tell the fortunes of all the winners, even last year&rsquo;s.</p>

<p>My turn came. I sat down next to her on the cold marble, and she told me to clasp my hands together. I laced my fingers, crossing my left thumb over my right.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re left-handed!&rdquo; she congratulated me.</p>

<p>&ldquo;No.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You may have learned to be right-handed, but really you&rsquo;re left-handed. Many creative people are.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Holding my hand in hers, she continued her assessment. I didn&rsquo;t care about money, she said, glancing at my cheap sandals. Taking in my robust build, she said I had incredible health and energy. Generally I had confidence in myself, but recently that confidence had been shaken. I was misunderstood as a child, so I had to fend for myself, make my own rules. &ldquo;They didn&rsquo;t get you,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;So you had to make up your own world as you went along. But did you have to make up such hard rules for yourself?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I thought of my microsecond onstage, of how one of my rules was that you don&rsquo;t rest on your laurels. Instead you minimize any achievement, because look how much farther you still have to go. On the other hand, if you still have so far to go, wouldn&rsquo;t it make sense to rest, if only for a few minutes, before venturing on?</p>

<p>My eyes filled with tears. Everything the palm reader had said was probably true for 90 percent of writers and 50 percent of the general population. But that didn&rsquo;t make it any less true for me.</p>

<h5>12.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>Walking back</strong></span> to the hotel, Osvaldo and I got into one of those wine-soaked fights that have no real beginning and seem as if they will never end. A fight in a foreign city, a fight that throws you so off balance that you think about setting out to walk home, even though home is thousands of miles away.</p>

<p>I kept coming back to a line he&rsquo;d thrown at me: &ldquo;Sometimes,&rdquo; he&rsquo;d said, &ldquo;I feel like I don&rsquo;t even know you.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Nobody here in New Orleans knew me, that was for sure. Not the man who&rsquo;d supposedly read and liked my novel; not the organizers who&rsquo;d dumped me on the wrong panel and couldn&rsquo;t even spell my name. Osvaldo was the person I felt closest to in the world. If he didn&rsquo;t know me, then no one did. I felt completely alone. So of course I went on the offensive, attacking him with all the rage I&rsquo;d kept under wraps until that moment. Hell hath no fury like a writer not known.</p>

<p>The fight raged, banked, then flared up again. Osvaldo stalked ahead, then drifted back. A few barbs later, it was I who stalked off.</p>

<p>I must have said something pretty bad, because Osvaldo locked me out of our hotel room. I wandered the empty, carpeted halls, high heels hanging from crooked fingers, muttering drunkenly to myself. Then I found the right door again, and I banged and shouted until he let me in.</p>

<p>The next morning, we were sheepish and gentle with each other. It was gorgeous out, the air soft and still a little cool. We had a few hours before we had to be at the airport, so we walked to the French Quarter for bookstore and gallery browsing, then coffee in Pirate&rsquo;s Alley, just down the lane from Faulkner Society headquarters, in the house where Faulkner had worked on his first novel.</p>

<p>We settled at an outside table across from the garden where the party had been held the night before. At the next table, a young woman was being fired. Her boss, a muscular young man with a frosted flattop, snarled, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a bigger bitch than you are.&rdquo; Down the cobblestone alley, I saw the head vampire and his apprentice, looking wan in the daylight.</p>

<p>Someone waved, then came over. It was Michael Cahill, winner of the 1996 novel prize. Since then his book, <em>A Nixon Man</em>, had come out to good reviews, and he and his wife had had their first child. I&rsquo;d spoken with him over the phone about agents and publishing the previous year; he&rsquo;d been extremely generous with his time and advice. At the time, I hadn&rsquo;t known how rare that was. I offered up a belated thanks.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You caught me when I was young and stupid,&rdquo; he said with a laugh.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Ah,&rdquo; I said. &ldquo;Now you wouldn&rsquo;t be so generous?&rdquo;</p>

<p>He shook his head. &ldquo;You have to be careful&rdquo; was all he would say. Then he had to go. He had a plane to catch.</p>

<p>So did we. During the flight I wondered about his comment. I even made some notes about it, so I wouldn&rsquo;t forget. What did you have to be careful of? People asking too much of you? Wanting too many favors? People writing about what you&rsquo;d said on the plane ride home?</p>

<h5>13.</h5>

<p><span class="smallcaps"><strong>Back in San Francisco,</strong></span> I have quickly been reabsorbed into my workaday world. New Orleans seems like a dream I can&rsquo;t quite remember. Yet parts of it keep coming back. I&rsquo;m in touch with Diane Freund, who writes from Bisbee, Arizona: &ldquo;The other night the moon looked like a bone trying to carve its way out of the night.&rdquo; We share trials and strategies for keeping the faith. She tells me to forget about being taken under someone&rsquo;s wing; what I need is to unfurl my own.</p>

<p>I aim to heed her advice, despite my wing-clipping full-time job, despite the tiny apartment I share with Osvaldo and his tubes of paint. I write when I can, a weekend wing-spreader. And, good late-twentieth-century American that I am, I see a therapist, who helps me root out the tender rot of my past and tries to train my gaze away from my weaknesses and toward my strengths.</p>

<p>One day she urges me to invent an animal guide, since no human ones are forthcoming. When I close my eyes, a bear lumbers into view &mdash; a big, female bear; one minute she has A.J. Verdelle&rsquo;s dreadlocks, then LuAnn&rsquo;s long, straight hair and jet-black nails. Though not exactly threatening, the creature is not particularly benevolent, either. I remember what A.J. said on her panel: &ldquo;If you make the bear talk, you win.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Hell, I&rsquo;m game.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Is there any help to be had?&rdquo; I ask the bear.</p>

<p>She takes her time answering &mdash; so long, in fact, that I start to think she&rsquo;s slipping into early hibernation. But finally she opens her mouth. &ldquo;Maybe there is,&rdquo; she says, enunciating precisely, &ldquo;and maybe there isn&rsquo;t.&rdquo;</p>

<p>So I made the bear talk. And I&rsquo;m not crazy about what she had to say.</p>

<p>Maybe the trick is to make the bear talk until you do like what she has to say. The bear could be a hairy muse, totem animal of inspiration and rough drafts.</p>

<p>Then again, maybe she&rsquo;s just a woman in a bear suit.</p>
